r.org/publication/newsmakers-0 |website=Belfer Center for Science and International Affairs |accessdate=27 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Taebi, Dr. ir. B. (Behnam) \u00e2\u20ac |url=https://www.dejongeakademie.nl/nl/leden/leden/14998 |website=www.dejongeakademie.nl |accessdate=27 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nTaebi studied Material Science and Engineering (2006) and received his Ph.D. in Philosophy of Technology (2010) at TU Delft in the Netherlands. He went to Harvard University in the US to perform his post-doctorate research where he established a firm tie with American research institute in ethical technology. His research interests are in energy ethics, nuclear ethics, responsible research and innovation (RRI) and engineering ethics. Taebi has finished a Veni project (2014-2018) and he is currently working on a joint RRI project on understanding controversies in energy technologies (both projects awarded by the Netherlands Organization for Scientific Research).\n\n==Academic career and coverage==\nHis work around the safety and ethical aspects of nuclear energy technology and systems or his contribution in critical nuclear debates have been extensively covered by media outlet in the USA such as [[New York Times]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Taebi |first1=Behnam |title=Opinion {{!}} The Burden of Nuclear Waste |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/30/opinion/30iht-edtaebi.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=27 January 2019 |date=29 August 2010}}</ref> [[Huffington Post]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Taebi |first1=Behnam |title=Volkswagen Scandal Reveals Design Flaws: The Need for Value Conscious Design |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/behnam-taebi/volkswagen-scandal-reveal_b_8280708.html?ec_carp=6394260751505444439 |website=Huffington Post |accessdate=27 January 2019 |date=13 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Taebi |first1=Behnam |title=Dutch Court Breaks Political Stalemate Over Climate Action |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/dutch-court-breaks-politi_us_5bb90426e4b0877501042281 |website=Huffington Post |accessdate=27 January 2019 |date=7 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Taebi |first1=Behnam |title=The Russian Nuclear Energy Proposal: An Offer You Can't Refuse |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/the-russian-nuclear-energ_us_5bb8fea3e4b0877501032cf0 |website=Huffington Post |accessdate=27 January 2019 |date=5 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Taebi |first1=Behnam |title=Why Rejecting Students Based on Nationality Is a Bad Idea for Universities and for the U.S. |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/why-rejecting-students-based-on-nationality-is-a-bad-idea-for-universities-and-for-the-us_us_5bae567de4b022a916cafc60 |website=Huffington Post |accessdate=27 January 2019 |date=13 March 2015}}</ref> [[Newsweek]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Behnam Taebi: Disposing of nuclear waste is a challenge for humanity {{!}} Opinion |url=https://www.newsweek.com/disposing-nuclear-waste-challenge-humanity-behnam-taebi-609468 |website=Newsweek |accessdate=27 January 2019 |language=en |date=15 May 2017}}</ref> Reuters,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Contributor |first1=Guest |title=Multinational repositories can address nuclear waste stockpile |url=http://blogs.reuters.com/great-debate-uk/2013/11/25/multinational-repositories-can-address-nuclear-waste-stockpile/ |website=Reuters Blogs |accessdate=27 January 2019 |date=25 November 2013}}</ref> and academic media such as National Interest <ref>{{cite web |last1=Kathleen Ara\u00fajo |first1=Behnam Taebi |title=Where Should Nuclear Waste be Dumped? |url=https://nationalinterest.org/feature/where-should-nuclear-waste-be-dumped-12961 |website=The National Interest |accessdate=27 January 2019 |language=en |date=26 May 2015}}</ref> and [[Thomson Reuters Foundation]] <ref>{{cite web |author=Thomson Reuters Foundation |title=Innovation to tackle climate change must be socially responsible |url=http://news.trust.org//item/20150420120307-djt7u/